metadata.name: Rite of Passage #62
metadata.description:
In life, we all take different paths, different rites of passage, and while the end is all that's ever true, we will still all view it and experience it in very different ways, like that masterpiece hanging on the wall at the end of our gallery visit. 
  

There are always things that we will never have the power to change, but at the same time, we determine the route, we influence the journey, we can choose the person we want to be. We'll look back on memories, we'll have regrets, and we'll think about what could have been - but unlike this artwork, in the end we won't be able to change the final output by simply pressing a number - so live well and be happy my friends. 

---------------------

Generative artwork by Sykcolo / @sykcoloart

Primary sale proceeds:
50% to Processing Foundation
50% to Savepakistan

Royalties:
50% to the original minter
50% to artist (me)

Press '2' to '4' to see what could have been + increase pixel density. 
Press 's' to save

Details:

150 hand-picked colour pallets (thanks to @SteveMakerspace for colour selection method)
2 Frame types
4 Art types
2 Times of day (light or dark background)

License: MIT

Happy Birthday fxhash

metadata.name: Dopamine Dreams #170
metadata.description:
Dopamine is a chemical released in the brain that makes you feel good.

Dopamine Dreams is an exploration of using patterns and geometric forms to create something that also makes you feel good; to create something that feels natural, as if it has sprung from the ground or appeared in the sky.  

In this work, there is a conversation happening between two modes for drawing the same grid. One is tight, geometric and calm. The other is loose, loopy and excited. They overlap, interlace and compete to fill the space.  One cannot exist without the other. Balance is the the key. Between them they create a landscape in which to dream. 

Generative artwork by AutoEclectus

Controls in live mode:
- After animation stops, press [s] to save a png

@autoeclectus everywhere - Twitter, Instagram and Masterdon. 
https://autoeclectus.art

metadata.name: Word-eating worms #67
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork.

An old letter recounts the problems and feelings caused by woodworms: worms known to eat not only the beams and wood of houses, but also old books. As an analogy to this daily occurrence, emoticons appear and with the good spirit of simplifying they begin to gnaw away so much literary flourish.

The piece puts in counterpoint two forms of communication: emoticons and traditional writing. Here an inevitable contrast is sought between the standardization of the feelings of emojis, and the excessive flourishes of texts, possibly already from other times.

Original flute (tap & frullato), cello (pizz) and marimba samplers.
((click to start sound))

[s] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)

metadata.name: #2023Streams #357
metadata.description:
#2023Streams is a color theory study that explores the use of algorithmically-generated color palettes and the juxtaposition of color harmonies keyed on a common hue. It brings playfulness to experimentation through the use of randomized features that control lighting, color assortment, and more, to create interesting, vibrant compositions.

I consider this piece—my generative "genesis"—to be a preliminary "sketch" whose desired outcomes are insights into color and light that might be applied to more advanced projects in the future.

This piece is also a first step for me, into the world of professional art. An art school dropout and software engineer by profession, I've been hacking on generative art projects, games, and interactive experiences for more than two decades. But now, in 2023, it's my time to focus and prioritize art and creativity.

Each image can be modified using the following keyboard commands:
- [d] Download the rendered image
- [j] Toggle between "jungle" (dimensional) and "jazz" (flat) modes
- [l] Toggle between light and dark backgrounds
- [e] Toggle between curved (ellipse) and flat (rectangle) shapes
- [s] Enable/disable shadows and highlights
- [t] Enable/disable transparency

Each image is rendered at 2400 x 2400 pixels by default. This should be suitable for an 8" x 8" output (at 300 dpi). Should you desire a higher resolution output, the image can be magnified up to 6x by clicking the "open ↗️" link and appending a density parameter to the URL, e.g. `&density=4` 

Lastly, #2023Streams is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license. This license allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build upon the material in any medium or format, so long as attribution is given to the creator. The license allows for commercial use.

What does this license mean? It means I invite you to have fun with your new piece, get creative and bring something new into the world.

I hope you enjoy these outputs as much as I do. Thank you for stopping by—and hopefully collecting.

metadata.name: Element #218
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Dencity #114
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: TIMEFRAMES #286
metadata.description:
‘What if you could take a photo of time?’

As a photographer myself, the act of taking photos is the act of freezing moments of time. Moments that will no longer ever be here. Each layer represents not only 3 aspects of time (hours, minutes and seconds) but also a very important aspect of photography: the light. Combining these two instances: the visual interpretation of light and the generative aspect of time - I present ‘TIMEFRAMES’.

12 selected colors. 5,688,900 possible combinations.

The less layers the rarer - ranging from 100% to 18%
All timeframes that have 42 on it like 4:20:00, 4:42:42, 4:20:42 are rarer - ranging from 50% to 42%
The darker the colors the rarer - ranging from 100% to 89%

Click on the image to Download. Created with @PureSpider’s template.

José Gasparian.
2022.
